@node "Introduction" "An Introduction To CheckMouse"

   Getting fed up of having to boot with no startup sequence and then run
 a special script which avoided loading programs in the WBStartup drawer
 every time my girlfriend wanted to play a game of something on my Amiga
 (just so that she didn't have to switch off all the programs that caused
 screen corruption or other problems with games such as using caches), I
 decided to look for an alternative way to make it simpler.

   First of all I thought of using a menu system.  This could also be
 tailored to running different games straight from the startup sequence or
 loading workbench or whatever I wanted to do.  I dismissed this when I
 found out it would mean opening a screen before workbench was loaded, thus
 meaning it had to be run after IPrefs.  I wasn't keen on this, because it
 would mean rearranging my custom startup sequence more than I thought
 necessary.

   I next thought about using a program that would check for any mouse
 buttons being held down, and do various things depending on which buttons
 were held down.  I had a small program of about 600 bytes which would
 execute a different startup sequence depending upon the state of the left
 mouse button.  Great!  Or so I thought, until I wanted to extend it to
 check if the right button was held down to execute a third variation on my
 startup sequence.  This meant having a similar utility which checked for
 just the right button.

   Because I thought that having two different utilities to do the job of
 what could be done in one a little wasteful, and also slightly useless
 because it would only execute a given script every time (something like
 "S:LeftMouse-Startup"), I decided to write my own utility to do something
 similar.

   The difference between CheckMouse and the utility I formerly used is that
 rather than execute a set script file, it sets the return codes used in
 script files to reflect the state of the mouse buttons.  Thus you can use
 CheckMouse in all sorts of scripts, and not just your startup sequence.

   Oh, and the (uncrunched) executable is only 548 bytes, whilst crunching
 using Imploder v4 (short root header) reduces the executable size
 to 512 bytes - a huge saving of 36 bytes!   ;-)

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "What's Needed To Use CheckMouse"

   @{u}REQUIREMENTS@{uu}

      I know I'll regret saying this, but CheckMouse @{i}should @{ui}work with any
 Amiga computer, and all versions of the operating system.

      A hard drive is not essential, but get one anyway, because they're
 really cheap compared to five years ago.  They also make using your Amiga
 @{b}so@{ub} much easier than with just floppy drives too!  Why else do you think all
 PC's and Macs come with a hard drive?

      Oh, and if you're using WB1.3, UPGRADE!  Okay, so when you bought your
 Amiga five or six (or maybe more) years ago, you didn't think you'd have to
 upgrade, but if you'd have bought a PC then, you'd have spent at least Ł400
 a year on it.  Why not spend Ł90 on WB3.1 (or, if you really can't afford
 that, about Ł20 on WB2) because it'll make things a lot better for you.

@endnode

@node "Usage" "How To Use CheckMouse"

   First of all, copy CheckMouse to your C: directory.  This way, it will be
 available in any scripts which use it (assuming the default path contains
 the C: directory).

   The next bit is the toughie - write a script/batch file which uses
 CheckMouse to decide what to do!  Please note - the script file must
 contain a failat command with a return code higher than 35 to prevent it
 from failing when CheckMouse is executed.  The best way to do this is to
 make sure the file has the line

      Failat 40

   somewhere before any running of the CheckMouse program!

   The following is a fragment of a script file which, when executed, uses
 CheckMouse to check if the left mouse button is held down.  If it is, a
 message is displayed.


      :
      :
   Failat 40
   C:CheckMouse
   If $RC EQ 5             ; Left mouse button held down

      Echo "Help! Help!  Someone's holding down the left mouse button!"

   EndIf
      :
      :


   By changing the value for which $RC is equal to, you can change the mouse
 buttons which are checked for in the script.  Click @{"here" link "Return_Codes" 0} for more
 information on the return codes used by CheckMouse.

   See also @{"Examples of using CheckMouse" link "Examples" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Return_Codes" "Return Codes From CheckMouse"

   Because CheckMouse uses the standard return code method of passing
 information back to the calling script file, the script file needs to check
 the return code to decide on which mouse button/s was/were pressed.

      Button/s pressed              Return Code
     +----------------+            +-----------+

       None                               0

       Left                               5
       Right                             10
       Middle                            20

       Left & Right                      15
       Left & Middle                     25
       Right & Middle                    30

       All three                         35


   If you want to check for NO buttons being pressed, you can use the OK
 argument with the 'IF' command.

   When checking for just a single button being pressed, the WARN, ERROR and
 FAIL arguments can be used with the 'IF' command - see @{"Examples" link "Examples" 0} for more
 details.

@endnode

@node "Examples" "Examples Of Using CheckMouse"

   @{b}Example 1@{ub}

      If you are only checking for the pressing of @{u}one@{uu} button, either left,
 right or middle, then you can use the WARN, ERROR and FAIL return codes
 respectively.

      Failat 40
      C:CheckMouse
      If OK          ; = If $RC EQ 0

         Echo "No buttons were pressed!"

      EndIf
         :
         :
      Echo "Checking for the left button ..."
      C:CheckMouse
      If WARN        ; = If $RC EQ 5

         Echo "The left mouse button was pressed!"

      EndIf
         :
         :
      Echo "Checking for the right button ..."
      C:CheckMouse
      If ERROR       ; = If $RC EQ 10

         Echo "The right mouse button was pressed!"

      EndIf
         :
         :
      Echo "Checking for the middle button ..."
      C:CheckMouse
      If FAIL        ; = If $RC EQ 20

         Echo "The middle button was pressed!"

      EndIf

   @{b}NOTE@{ub}:  If when the above 'script' is executed you hold down both the left
 button AND the right button, then the following would be output ...

      The left button was pressed!
      The right button was pressed!

   For how to use CheckMouse with combinations of buttons, see the next
 example ...


   @{b}Example 2@{ub}

   If you wanted to do a variety of things upon execution of a script, and
 wish to use CheckMouse to decide what to do, then it is a little more
 complex than before.  Also, if you wanted to check for combinations of
 buttons as well as single button presses, then you have to be careful to
 check for the combinations of any buttons that you are also checking for as
 single buttons.

      Failat 40
      C:CheckMouse
      If $RC EQ 5       ; Left button pressed

         Echo "The left button was pressed!"

      Else

         C:CheckMouse
         If $RC EQ 15   ; Left & right buttons pressed

            Echo "The left and right buttons were pressed!"

         EndIf

      EndIf

   The above script, when executed, would output the following if both the
 left and the right mouse buttons were held down ...

      "The left button was pressed!"
      "The left and right buttons were pressed!"

   To avoid this, you can switch round the '5' and the '15' in the If
 statements, which would first check for both the left and right buttons,
 and only if this didn't happen check for the left button.  If a script file
 doesn't do what is expected of it, maybe you need to change round the order
 in which button presses are checked.

   @{b}Please note:@{ub}

      The 'If $RC EQ x' statement itself will set the return code $RC to
 reflect the fact that it has either been successfully executed or not.
 Because of this, if you wish to check for more than one button, or
 combination of, @{u}you must either:@{uu}

   1)  Run CheckMouse again, to set the return codes back to what is
       relevant depending upon the states of the mouse buttons.  The only
       problems this should cause is that script execution takes slightly
       longer, and the mouse buttons must be held down during the duration
       of all the checking so that the script executes correctly.  For an
       example of this, see my startup-sequence, below.

  @{b}or@{ub}

  2)  Assign another environment variable to hold the value of $RC @{u}BEFORE@{uu}
      you do the checking of values using if-statements.  For example ...

         Failat 40
         C:CheckMouse
         SetEnv MouseButtons $RC
         If $MouseButtons EQ 15       ; Left & right buttons pressed

            Echo "The left and right buttons were pressed!"
       
         Else

            If $MouseButtons EQ 5   ; Left  button pressed

               Echo "The left button was pressed!"

            EndIf

         EndIf

      This script is similar to the previous one, with the main difference being CheckMouse is only run once!

   The following is my current startup-sequence.  All I did to my old one
 was to delete the Setpatch line and rename it to S:Normal_Startup.  This
 way, by holding down the left button upon startup my girlfriend can play
 games (and so can I if I want to :), and on holding down the right button
 I can go straight into my preferred programming environment without having
 to load Workbench first.

      C:SetPatch >NIL:
      Failat 40
      C:CheckMouse
      If Error        ; Right button held down

         Execute s:Programming_Startup

      Else

         C:CheckMouse
         If Warn    ; Left button held down

            Execute S:Games_Startup

         Else        ; Either no buttons or middle button held down

            Execute s:Normal_Startup

         EndIf

      EndIf

@endnode

